{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474862"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12439"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.18,0.25,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4947"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48710"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4947"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1835"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"9485"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45857"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48710"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a two-day history of right upper arm swelling. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His weight and height are at the 75th percentile. The only abnormal physical finding is an immobile, non-tender mass on the proximal humerus. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chondroblastoma","Ewing sarcoma","Osteoid osteoma","Osteosarcoma","Osteochondroma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a 3.5 cm bony protrusion with a cartilage cap on the proximal metaphysis, consistent with the diagnosis of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteochondroma\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the most common type of benign bone tumour, typically developing in the metaphysis of long bones (proximal humerus, distal femur). It usually manifests between 10-30 years of age, with males at higher risk. Typical symptoms include a painless palpable mass near a joint, limited range of motion, bone deformities, and possibly pathological fractures. Radiographic findings include a sessile or pedunculated bony protrusion with a cartilage cap. This type of tumour has a 1% chance of malignant transformation and usually does not require treatment unless symptoms develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChondroblastomas\u003C/strong\u003E may involve the proximal humerus but usually develop in the epiphysis instead of the metaphysis. They typically present with constant joint pain and swelling. X-ray findings usually show a well-defined osteolytic lesion with a sclerotic rim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEwing sarcomas\u003C/strong\u003E often develop in the diaphysis of long bones and pelvic bones. This highly malignant tumour typically presents with progressively worsening pain, localised erythema, and systemic symptoms, which are absent in this case. X-rays typically show osteolytic bone lesions and an onion-skin appearance of the periosteum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoid osteomas\u003C/strong\u003E can form at any age and may involve the metaphysis of long bones, but patients usually present with constant and intense pain that worsens at night and is responsive to NSAIDs. Radiographic findings show a bony mass with a radiolucent core, surrounded by perifocal sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcomas\u003C/strong\u003E also preferentially develop in males from 10-30 years of age, but have a characteristic X-ray showing a sunburst appearance of lytic bone lesions (moth-eaten appearance +/- Codman triangles), and possible osteosclerotic lesions. This type of tumour typically presents with localised and progressive pain that worsens at night, systemic symptoms, localised swelling, and erythema, similar to Ewing sarcoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Osteochondroma is the most common benign bone tumour, typically presenting as a painless mass near a joint in adolescents or young adults.","Osteochondromas are characterized radiographically by a bony protrusion with a cartilage cap, usually arising from the metaphysis of long bones.","Most osteochondromas do not require treatment unless they cause symptoms or show rapid growth, with only a 1% risk of malignant transformation."],"references":["De Salvo S, Pavone V, Coco S, Dell\u2019Agli E, Blatti C, Testa G. Benign bone tumors: an overview of what we know today. Journal of Clinical Medicine. 2022 Jan 28;11(3):699.","Ferguson JL, Turner SP. Bone cancer: diagnosis and treatment principles. American family physician. 2018 Aug 15;98(4):205-13.","Chen W, DiFrancesco LM. Chondroblastoma: an update. Archives of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine. 2017 Jun;141(6):867-71."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19047"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},